<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How accurate are yarn yardage estimates?", answer: "Yarn yardage estimates give you a starting point based on average patterns in each category and yarn weight. Actual usage varies with your personal gauge, stitch pattern complexity, and size within the category. Cables, colorwork, and textured stitches can use 15 to 30 percent more yarn than stockinette. Always buy 10 to 20 percent extra to account for your individual tension and to keep a same-dye-lot reserve for repairs." },
  { question: "Why should I buy from the same dye lot?", answer: "Yarn is dyed in batches called dye lots, and the same color from different lots can vary noticeably when knit or crocheted side by side. Buying all skeins from the same dye lot ensures consistent color throughout your project. Check the label — the dye lot number is usually printed alongside the color number. If you need more yarn later and cannot find the same lot, try to alternate rows between the old and new lot to blend the difference." },
  { question: "What yarn weight is worsted?", answer: "Worsted weight is Craft Yarn Council category 4, also called medium, afghan, or aran weight. It is the most common weight for knitting and crochet projects in North America. A standard gauge is 16 to 20 stitches per 4 inches on US 7 to 9 needles (4.5 to 5.5 mm). Worsted yarn is versatile, working for hats, sweaters, blankets, and accessories, and it produces a fabric that balances warmth and drape." },
  { question: "Should I buy extra yarn for gauge swatches?", answer: "Yes — always buy extra yarn to account for a gauge swatch. A 4 by 4 inch swatch typically uses 10 to 30 yards depending on the yarn weight, and you may need to knit multiple swatches to find the right needle size. Add at least one extra skein beyond your calculated needs so you have plenty of yarn for swatching, gauge adjustments, and any repairs down the road." },
  { question: "What do the numbers 0 to 7 mean on yarn labels?", answer: "The numbers 0 to 7 are the standard yarn weight categories defined by the Craft Yarn Council. 0 is lace, 1 is super fine or fingering, 2 is fine or sport, 3 is light or DK, 4 is medium or worsted, 5 is bulky, 6 is super bulky, and 7 is jumbo. These categories help you substitute yarns in a pattern and estimate yardage for a given project size." }
]) %>

